Detroit Shock on Friday night.

related.description: Former Detroit Pistons star Bill Laimbeer is expected to replace Gregg Williams as the coach of the WNBA's Detroit Shock this week, the Detroit Free Press reported Friday.

article.headline: Sales helps Miracle keep Shock winless
article.linkText: Laimbeer loses debut as Shock routed by Miracle
article.story:
AUBURN HILLS, Mich. (AP) -- Bill Laimbeer knew he had a lot of work ahead of him when he accepted his first head coaching assignment. On Friday night, he found out just how much. Nykesha Sales matched her season-high with 24 points and the Orlando Miracle spoiled Laimbeer's debut with an 80-59 victory over the winless Detroit Shock. Detroit's WNBA-record worst start extended to 0-11, tying the league mark for longest losing streak in league history. "Well, I knew this wasn't going to be easy,'' Laimbeer said. "I've only had one practice with the team, so tonight was a chance for me to watch and learn. I know a lot more about this group than I did when we started.'' The Shock join baseball's Tigers (0-11) and the NFL's Lions (0-12) as Detroit teams to lose at least their first 11 games of the season within the past year. Taj McWilliams-Franklin had a season-high 17 points for Orlando (6-3), while Shannon Johnson added 10. "We knew Detroit was struggling,'' said first-year Orlando coach Dee Brown, like Laimbeer a former NBA player. "But we knew they would come out with a lot of energy having a new coach and trying to get a win at home, so we wanted to get a jump on them early.'' Rookie Swin Cash had a career-high 20 points for Detroit and Dominique Canty added 10. "I think today is still a positive,'' Canty said. "Bill knows how to win, and he's a very laid-back, fun guy. He's going to keep us up, and that's what we need right now.'' Detroit led 8-6, but the Miracle responded with a 21-6 run with McWilliams-Franklin and Clarisse Machanguana each scoring six points. Orlando led 39-23 at halftime, outshooting Detroit 50 percent to 29.6 percent, and forcing 11 turnovers while only committing two. "We just played well as a team tonight,'' McWilliams-Franklin said. "We were focused and we played good fundamental basketball.'' The Miracle ended any Detroit hopes for a win by starting the second half with a 6-1 run. That put Orlando up by 21 points, and the Miracle led by as many as 26 down the stretch. "The biggest thing I learned tonight is that our offense needs a total overhaul,'' Laimbeer said. "When teams take away our initial thrust, which everyone will do, we don't have a second option. We need a second option and a third one and a fourth one.'' Game notes
Detroit has lost seven of its last eight games against Orlando. ... Laimbeer, who has his Pistons jersey hanging from the Palace rafters, replaced Greg Williams on Wednesday. ... Orlando has won four straight on the road. ... Orlando's record for margin of victory is 29, set against Detroit in August 2000. ... Attendance was reported at 5,862, an improvement over the league-record-low crowd of 3,315 in Detroit's previous home game.
